> HN> math@asterix.rz.tu-clausthal.de (Torsten Hiddessen) writes:

> TH>> otherwise it will overheat after 20 minutes of heavy load.

> HN> Question from a hardware-illiterate programmer:  Is a CPU chip really
> HN> getting hotter with a "heavy load" than when idle?  Isn't the CPU always
> HN> 100% "busy" (in some kind of "idle loop" if nothing else to do)?

>Yes, you're right. THE CPU IS ALWAYS VERY BUSY, especially on an Amiga. Due to
>the multitasking the processor can't stay on-cache even when no process takes
>any processing-time, so it always has to go off-chip for memory-accesses. I
>don't know really if the chip would 'cool-off' if it doesn't have to go off chip
>for memory accesses, but in the Amiga it certainly doesn't.

Nope, he isn't right. When there is nothing to do for the CPU in an Amiga,
Exec issues the STOP instruction. That one stops the CPU from fetching and
executing instructions. Only an external interrupt will wake it up again. It
seems reasonable that the power-usage is lower during this time (although I'm
not sure about this).
